dom","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Škotska, United Kingdom","Morayshire, Scotland, Scotland":"Moray, Škotska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"about 1100–":"okolo 1100–Zesnulá","1100–Male":"1100–Zesnulý","1109–Female":"1109–Zesnulá","1112–1160":"1112–1160","1135–Male":"1135–Zesnulý","1140–Male":"1140–Zesnulý","1100–Female":"1100–Zesnulá","about 1140":"okolo 1140","1135":"1135","1112":"1112","1100":"1100","about 1112":"okolo 1112","1140":"1140","about 1100":"okolo 1100","1160":"1160","1109":"1109","Smailholm Tower, Kelso, Roxburgh, Scotland":"Kelso, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","United Kingdom":"United Kingdom","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Skotsko, United Kingdom","Morayshire, Scotland, Scotland":"Moray, Skotsko, United Kingdom"},"da":{"about 1100–":"omkring 1100–Afdød","1100–Male":"1100–Afdød","1109–Female":"1109–Afdød","1112–1160":"1112–1160","1135–Male":"1135–Afdød","1140–Male":"1140–Afdød","1100–Female":"1100–Afdød","about 1140":"omkring 1140","1135":"1135","1112":"1112","1100":"1100","about 1112":"omkring 1112","1140":"1140","about 1100":"omkring 1100","1160":"1160","1109":"1109","Smailholm Tower, Kelso, Roxburgh, Scotland":"Kelso, Roxburghshire, Skotland","Scotland":"Skotland","United Kingdom":"United Kingdom","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Skotland, United Kingdom","Morayshire, Scotland, Scotland":"Moray, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1100–":"circa 1100–Overleden","1100–Male":"1100–Overleden","1109–Female":"1109–Overleden","1112–1160":"1112–1160","1135–Male":"1135–Overleden","1140–Male":"1140–Overleden","1100–Female":"1100–Overleden","about 1140":"circa 1140","1135":"1135","1112":"1112","1100":"1100","about 1112":"circa 1112","1140":"1140","about 1100":"circa 1100","1160":"1160","1109":"1109","Smailholm Tower, Kelso, Roxburgh, Scotland":"Kelso, Roxburghshire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland","United Kingdom":"Verenigd Koninkrijk","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Morayshire, Scotland, Scotland":"Moray, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1100–":"about 1100–Deceased","1100–Male":"1100–Deceased","1109–Female":"1109–Deceased","1112–1160":"1112–1160","1135–Male":"1135–Deceased","1140–Male":"1140–Deceased","1100–Female":"1100–Deceased","about 1140":"about 1140","1135":"1135","1112":"1112","1100":"1100","about 1112":"about 1112","1140":"1140","about 1100":"about 1100","1160":"1160","1109":"1109","Smailholm Tower, Kelso, Roxburgh, Scotland":"Kelso, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","United Kingdom":"United Kingdom","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","Morayshire, Scotland, Scotland":"Moray, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Alexander","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish, English, German, and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Alexander</i>, classical Greek <i>Alexandros</i>, which probably originally meant ‘repulser of men (i.e. of the enemy)’, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to repel’ + <i>andros</i>, genitive of <i>anēr</i> ‘man’. Its popularity in the Middle Ages was due mainly to the Macedonian conqueror, Alexander the Great (356–323  BC ) - or rather to the hero of the mythical versions of his exploits that gained currency in the so-called Alexander Romances. The name was also borne by various early Christian saints, including a patriarch of Alexandria (<i>c.</i> 250–326  AD ), whose main achievement was condemning the Arian heresy. The Gaelic form of the personal name is <i>Alasdair</i>, which has given rise to a number of Scottish and Irish patronymics, for example   McAllister  . <i>Alexander</i> is a common personal name in Scotland, often representing an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Spanish   Alejandro  , Italian   Alessandro  , Arabic or Assyrian/Chaldean   Iskandar   and   Iskander  , and their derivatives, e.g. Greek patronymic <b>Alexandropoulos</b>.","Jewish: from the adopted personal name <i>Alexander</i> (see 1 above) or shortened from the eastern Ashkenazic (originally Slavic) patronymics <b>Aleksandrovich</b> or <b>Alexandrowicz</b>.","History: A number of Scotch-Irish families of this name landed at New York in the early 18th century. By 1746, six of them were established in NC. Others came in through Philadelphia, for example Archibald Alexander, who came from Londonderry in northern Ireland in 1736 and established himself in VA. — The Revolutionary general William Alexander (1726–83) was always known as ‘Lord Sterling’ to his compatriots, although his claim to the title was denied by the College of Arms in London. His father, James Alexander, was a Jacobite who had fled to New York after the failure of the Jacobite rising in 1715. The claim to the title arose in connection with their ancestor Sir William Alexander, a courtier and poet at the court of King James VI of Scotland (James I of England), who created him Earl of Stirling in 1633."],"variants":[{"name":"Alley","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ally</i>, <i>Alli</i>, as forms such as <i>Johannes filius Alli</i> (Norfolk, 1205) make clear. It may be a pet form of   Alexander  ,   Alan  ,   Alice  , or   Alison  , or a survival of Old Danish <i>Alli</i>, Old Swedish <i>Alle</i>, found as <i>Alli</i> in the Domesday Book.","In some cases also an altered form of French <b>Hallé</b> (see   Halle   2) or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname.","Variant of   Allee   2, a surname of French origin."]},{"name":"Aleck","meanings":["English: perhaps a short form of the personal name   Alexander  ."]},{"name":"Alejandro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Juan, Jose, Luis, Alfredo, Manuel, Miguel, Pablo, Angel, Armando, Felipe, Gerardo, Jesus.","Spanish: from the personal name <i>Alejandro</i>, an equivalent of   Alexander  . Compare   De Alejandro  ."]},{"name":"Alessandro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Nicola, Biagio, Domenic, Natale, Rocco, Salvatore, Angelo, Antonio, Carlo, Carmello, Carmin, Enzo.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Alessandro</i>, from classical Greek <i>Alexandros</i> (see   Alexander  )."]},{"name":"Alexandrou","meanings":["Greek: patronymic from the genitive case of the personal name <i>Alexandros</i> (see   Alexander  )."]},{"name":"McAllister","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Alasdair</b> ‘son of <i>Alasdair</i>’, the Gaelic form of the personal name   Alexander  .","History: <i>MacAlister</i> is the name of a Scottish Highland clan claiming descent from Alasdair Mòr Mac Dòmhnaill, a younger son of Domhnall mac Raghnaill, founder of Clan Donald (see   McDonald  )."]},{"name":"Alexandre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Pierre, Michel, Jacques, Julien, Rodolphe, Andre, Cecile, Colette, Dominique, Eunide, Francoise, Georges.  Spanish Jose, Fernando, Adela, Amandio, Amarante, Ana, Beatriz, Carlos, Claudio, Consuelo, Isidro, Joaquina.  Portuguese Joaquim, Aderito, Serafim.","French, Portuguese, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and Mauritian: from the personal name <i>Alexandre</i> (see   Alexander  )."]},{"name":"Aleksanyan","meanings":["Armenian: patronymic from the personal name <i>Aleksan</i>, a short form of <i>Aleksander</i> (see   Alexander  ). This form (transliteration) of the surname is found mainly in Armenia and Russia."]},{"name":"Alexandra","meanings":["English: variant of   Alexander  , apparently from the feminine form of the personal name. — Note: It is possible that in the population figure published by the US Census Bureau (which dropped from 644 in the year 2000 to 440 in the year 2010) the female personal name <i>Alexandra</i> of some American bearers is also counted as a surname. Some of these bearers may be from countries, such as Indonesia, where (hereditary) surnames are not in general use."]},{"name":"Aleksandrov","meanings":["Russian, Bulgarian, Macedonian, and Serbian: patronymic from the personal name <i>Aleksandr</i>, <i>Aleksandar</i> (see   Alexander  ). Compare   Alexandrov  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Alexander was born about 1100, in Scotland. She had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Sir Alexander de Cadella Thane of Calder."},"et":{"about 1100–":"umbes 1100–Surnud","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1109–Female":"1109–Surnud","1112–1160":"1112–1160","1135–Male":"1135–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","about 1140":"umbes 1140","1135":"1135","1112":"1112","1100":"1100","about 1112":"umbes 1112","1140":"1140","about 1100":"umbes 1100","1160":"1160","1109":"1109","Smailholm Tower, Kelso, Roxburgh, Scotland":"Kelso, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","United Kingdom":"United Kingdom","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Morayshire, Scotland, Scotland":"Moray, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1100–":"noin 1100–Kuollut","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1109–Female":"1109–Kuollut","1112–1160":"1112–1160","1135–Male":"1135–Kuollut","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1100–Female":"1100–Kuollut","about 1140":"noin 1140","1135":"1135","1112":"1112","1100":"1100","about 1112":"noin 1112","1140":"1140","about 1100":"noin 1100","1160":"1160","1109":"1109","Smailholm Tower, Kelso, Roxburgh, Scotland":"Kelso, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","United Kingdom":"Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Morayshire, Scotland, Scotland":"Moray, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1100–":"environ 1100–Décédée","1100–Male":"1100–Décédé","1109–Female":"1109–Décédée","1112–1160":"1112–1160","1135–Male":"1135–Décédé","1140–Male":"1140–Décédé","1100–Female":"1100–Décédée","about 1140":"environ 1140","1135":"1135","1112":"1112","1100":"1100","about 1112":"environ 1112","1140":"1140","about 1100":"environ 1100","1160":"1160","1109":"1109","Smailholm Tower, Kelso, Roxburgh, Scotland":"Kelso, Roxburghshire, Écosse","